<Review ID>8870394
<Product Name>Creative Zen V Plus 2 GB Portable Media Player (Black/Green)
<Title>The best I've found for audiobooks
<Date>Wed Dec 12 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>I have used a 2 GB Creative Zen V Plus for over a year almost exclusively for listening to audiobooks: mostly downloaded from libraries supplied through Overdrive (WMA-DRM), some from Audible.  I have also found it easy to rip books (or music) from CD's to the player using the Creative software or Windows Media Player.   I find the Zen V Plus well suited for audiobook listening. You can have up to ten bookmarks, as well as bookmarks for more than one book at a time. All bookmarks for a given book are automatically deleted when the book is  deleted from the player, and bookmarks can be individually deleted when no longer needed. If I turn off the player while a book is playing, it will resume in the same place when turned on. It is easy to reverse a little or a lot if I want to hear a few lines, or a whole passage, again.   The Zen V Plus is not perfect.  As mentioned in other reviews, it sometimes freezes and must be reset. Then I use fast forward to get back to my place. For me, that minor inconvenience is outweighed by its versatility.    While the Zen V Plus has not been without problems, the support has been good. My first Zen V Plus experienced a total failure while in the warranty period.  It was easy to contact the support team through the Creative web site and, after confirming that I had already followed the appropriate trouble-shooting steps, they quickly arranged a replacement at no cost to me. The short (3 month) warranty is regrettable.  Service beyond warranty is expensive, so the player is effectively "disposable" after the warranty period. After my second player had passed warranty, it  had a serious (but not fatal) problem that was solved by reformatting and a firmware upgrade. With a trouble-shooting utility and instructions for the upgrade, provided on the Creative support web site, it was easy.  Although I find high audio quality less critical with audiobooks than with music, I upgraded the earphones with Shure E2C for comfort.   The Zen V series offers a lot of features of more or less value to me. I use the FM radio function and it works very well, even in areas where reception is normally poor. The player has a handy "idle sleep" function and a "snooze timer". I have no idea how these two features differ, but both seem to turn off the player after a (selectable) number of minutes. It is easy to use the Zen V series player for podcast listening and as a removable data storage drive. Files can be transferred through the Creative software, or by drag and drop (or cut and paste) in the Windows Explorer. I much appreciate, and have used, the ability to customize menus and settings.  I have little use for the Zen V Plus sound recording, the photo and video capabilities, or the basic PIM organizer application. I imagine the Playlist and DJ functions are valuable for listening to music. I did find it very easy to make playlists when I tried it out with some music during the first week I had the player.  Three members of my family also have Zen V Plus players for listening to audiobooks (and some music). If someone knows of a player that will handle a variety of audiobook formats (and bookmarks) as well as this one without freezing periodically, I'd love to hear about it.  
<Overall>4

